          Superelements and Modules User’s Guide External Superelement Usage in SOL 400648 Main Index External Superelement Usage in SOL 400 Version 2021.1 extends the External Superelement capability to SOL 400 and includes several minor enhancements to external superelement analysis in general. It is important to note that the program (MSC Nastran) will create external part superelements with component mode reduction or Guyan reduction for inclusion in a nonlinear analysis. All nonlinearities are assumed to exist in the residual structure only since it is understood that part superelements will only have linear behavior. The following use cases are supported. 1.Create external superelements in linear solution sequences (SOLs 101 through 112) and assemble in SOL 400 for both nonlinear and multidisciplinary analyses. The procedure is the same as for assembly runs in the linear solution sequences for both nonlinear and multidisciplinary analyses. The procedure is the same as for assembly runs in the linear solution sequences . It should be noted that if the applied loads come from an external superelement(s) but no loads are applied in the assembly, then the displacements will be null. A dummy LOAD Case Control command is required in the assembly run to include the loads from the external superelement(s). 2.Create linear external superelements in a SOL 400 multidisciplinary analysis a.With PARAM,AUTOQSET,YES SOL 400 CEND ANALYSIS = MODES $ doesn’t really matter which analysis type PARAM,AUTOQSET,YES EXTSEOUT METHOD=300 BEGIN BULK ASETi (static boundary points) b.With QSETi/SPOINT SOL 400 CEND ANALYSIS = MODES $ doesn’t really matter which analysis type EXTSEOUT METHOD=300 BEGIN BULK ASETi (static boundary points) QSETI (dynamic boundary points) SPOINT (component boundary points) 3.Create pre-stressed external superelements in a SOL 400 linear perturbation step. a.With PARAM,AUTOQSET,YES SOL 400 CEND

          649 CHAPTER 12 External Superelement Examples Main Index SUBCASE 100 STEP 100 ANALYSIS=NLSTATICS NLPARM = 1 STEP 200 ANALYSIS = MODES $ doesn’t really matter which analysis type PARAM,AUTOQSET,YES EXTSEOUT METHOD=300 BEGIN BULK ASETi (static boundary points) b.With QSETi/SPOINT SOL 400 CEND SUBCASE 100 STEP 100 ANALYSIS=NLSTATICS NLPARM = 1 STEP 200 ANALYSIS = MODES $ doesn’t really matter which analysis type EXTSEOUT METHOD=300 BEGIN BULK ASETi (static boundary points) QSETI (dynamic boundary points) SPOINT (component boundary points) In general, the existing external superelement modeling capability of MSC Nastran is also available in SOL 400, which means the standard creation, assembly and solve and data recovery steps. The procedure is described in the MSC Nastran Superelements and Modules User’s Guide and in the MSC Nastran Quick Reference Guide under the description of EXTSEOUT (Case) Case Control command. 1.There are two methods of data recovery in the external superelement: •3-step method for external superelement generation, assembly and data recovery •A simplified 2-step method in which the assembly and solve and data recovery steps are consolidated into a single step. Both the methods support export of full/reduced component model data for sharing with design groups or vendors. Both methods support advanced nonlinear elements defined by PBARN1, PBEMN1, PRODN1,

          Superelements and Modules User’s Guide SOL 400 3-Step Method650 Main Index PSHLN1, PSLDN1, and PSHEARN entries. 2.A new keyword is added to the EXTSEOUT Case Control command to specify whether the q-set (dynamic degrees-of-freedom) are defined on ASET1 or QSET1 entries in the exported file. By default all q-set DOFs are written to QSET1 entries which means they will appear in the assembly modes. By specifying ASET, the q-set DOFs are written to ASET1 entries and will be synthesized in the assembly modes. 3.3-step data recovery enhancements Step 1: Creation run. •Specify the EXTSEOUT Case Control command to export the boundary matrices. •Specify scr=no on the command line to save the database for Step 3 restart Step 2: Assembly run •Attach the boundary matrices from Step 1. •Specify EXTDROUT Case Control command to select the media to store the boundary solution matrix (displacements, velocities, and accelerations) and labels; e.g., eigenvalues, time steps, load factors, etc. Step 3: Data recovery run •Restart the database from Step 1. •Attach the solution matrix and labels from Step 2. •Specify EXTDRIN Case Control command. Acoustic External Superelement Creation An acoustic external superelement which contains both the fluid cavity and the fluid-structural boundary may be created with the EXTSEOUT Case Control command. For an acoustic external superelement, the component modes and their associated reduced stiffness, mass, etc. matrices are computed separately for the fluid and structure. If QSETi and SPOINT Bulk Data entries are used to define the generalized coordinates then there must be a sufficient number to accommodate both the fluid and structure modes. If there are insufficient generalized coordinates then the program will truncate both the fluid and structural modes proportionally. It is for this reason that PARAM,AUTOQSET,YES is strongly recommended to avoid potential modal truncation. Fluid points may also be specified on the boundary of the superelement using the ASETi entry. The ACMS feature (see the DOMAINSOLVER ACMS (PARTOPT=DOF) Executive Control statement in the MSC Nasiran Quick Reference Guide is fully integrated with the creation of an external acoustic superelement. The ACMS feature (see the DOMAINSOLVER ACMS (PARTOPT=DOF) Executive Control statement in the MSC Nasiran Quick Reference Guide is fully integrated with the creation of an external acoustic superelement. However, free-fixed or free-free fluid or structure boundaries are not permitted with ACMS. Multiple External Superelements with Fluid Cavities Before Nastran V2017.1, only a single external superelement with a fluid cavity could be attached in the assembly run. Starting with V2017.1, multiple external superelements with fluid cavities can be attached in the assembly run. A typical application is modeling each tire with a fluid cavity in a separate external superelement. A simple example with two external superelements with each containing a separate fluid cavity, may be found in the tpl\extfluidse folder.           Superelements User’s Guide Introduction648 Main Index Introduction ACCESS POINTS are an advanced feature of external superelements. They allow selected interior GRID points to be brought downstream without putting them into the A-set. A good example of this is locations where accelerometers are to be attached to the structure. Placing these GRID points into the B-set causes them to be constrained during the calculation of the component modes and placing them into the C-set complicates the calculations during component modal synthesis. This functionality has been available in MSC Nastran since version 2010. They will be referred via ACCSSPT (the name of the Bulk Data entry) in this section. Once, the component modes are calculated with boundary conditions selected by the user, MPC equations are created relating ACCSSPT displacement to A-Set dofs (both physical and component modes) during the assembly process. The associated GRID points are copied into the input files for the external superelement, along with the ACCSSPT entries Thus, in the run using the external superelement, the ACCSSPT DOFs are placed in the M-set of the residual structure and the MPC equations relating the motion of the ACCSSPT to External Superlement A-set motion are added.
          Thus, The ACCSSPT functionality enables some of the following advantages. •Free-Free external SE’s •Allows for what if studies, by changing the input DMIG directly •Participation factors on external SE responses •Loads on the external SE grids which are not in the external superelement A-set •Brings internal grids and acoustics into residual structure without adding them to the A-set of the external superelement Background A simple example is used to demonstrate how an ACCSSPT works. In this model, for simplicity, the component has only 2 GRID points and we will only consider each GRID to have 1 dof. GRID point 2 is the exterior point (T-set) and GRID point 3 will be an ACCSSPT. We will use component modal synthesis and obtain 1 mode associated with dof 4(the Q-set). Spring K23 is a unit spring and there is

          649 CHAPTER 13 Access Points Main Index a unit mass on GRID point 3. Without going through the math, the boundary transformation for this superelement will be: U3 = GOA×UA = [1.0 1.0]{U2 U4}T This has the form of an MPC equation and can be written as such. 0.0 = - U3 +1.0×U2 + 1.0×U4 So we now have a reduced superelement, containing only exterior dof for GRID point 2 and SPOINT 4, but we have an MPC equation which relate s the displacement of GRID point 3 to the displacements of those dof. When Nastran create s the input file for the external superelement, it contains the external dof (GRID point 2 and SPOINT 4), but it also contains GRID point 3 and the MPC equation. The MPC equation will be in the database, op2 file, or DMIG, depending on which you select to use. So the motion of GRID point 3 is now fully represented, even although it is not an exterior point for the superelement. Loads may be applied to it and it may be constrained (if you use AUTOMSET=YES to allow the program to move it from the M-set to the S-set by re-writing the MPC equation) or even in the A-set of the residual structure. MSC Nastran Interface and Usage a.External SE generation run: Specify the interior GRID points which you want to be available after reduction on ACCSSPT entries. Example Skeleton: SOL 103 CEND EXTSEOUT(ASMBULK=MANQ, EXTID=id, DMIGPCH) BEGIN BULK ACCSSPT b.Create the assembly run with the external superelement included. The attachment process is method dependent and best described in Chapter 12: External Superelement Examples . To avoid redundancy this will not be described here. The attachment process can also be found in the MSC Nastran Quick Reference Guide under the case control command description of EXTSEOUT (Case) . c.The program automatically creates residual vectors for the dof associated with the ACCSSPT entries to improve the accuracy. (Note that in the example above there are no residual vectors required, as the A-set motion can represent all possible motion of the ACCSSPT) d.As they are placed in the M-Set of the residual structure constraining them will cause a set conflict as a dof cannot be in A-set and M-set simultaneously. This can be avoided by using PARAM,AUTOMSET,YES .
